</summary><link length="0" href="http://www.podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/audio.wnyc.org/otm/otm052314_cms372760.mp3" type="audio/mpeg" rel="enclosure"></link><category term="album_reviews"></category><category term="drake"></category><category term="life"></category><category term="music"></category><category term="technology"></category><category term="tldr"></category><category term="tldr_podcast"></category><category term="tldr_show"></category><category term="twittercard"></category></entry><entry><title>Health Inspectors Are Using Yelp Reviews To Target Dirty Restaurants
</title><link href="http://www.onthemedia.org/story/health-inspectors-are-using-yelp-reviews-target-dirty-restaurants/" rel="alternate"></link><updated>2014-05-23T10:59:30-04:00</updated><id>http://www.onthemedia.org/story/health-inspectors-are-using-yelp-reviews-target-dirty-restaurants/</id><summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6320a1.htm?s_cid=mm6320a1_w" target="_blank"&gt;The Center for Disease Control&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span&gt; &lt;/span&gt;says that NYC health inspectors have been using Yelp reviews to ferret out local restaurants which were giving patrons food poisoning. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The system is pretty elegant, insofar as you can describe anything used for tracking diarrhea outbreaks as elegant. The inspectors looked for keywords associated with food poisoning. Then, two or more people had to have used those words and reported that a place made them sick. Lastly, the incubation period had to be under 10 hours. If a restaurant met all the criteria, health inspectors would visit to see if something was amiss. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The only obvious problem that comes to mind is that now that this formula is public, it's gameable by jerks. If you run a pizzeria and want to sabotage your competitors, you now know the formula that merits NY health department attention. But that said -- there's always been an incentive for businesses to trash talk each other on Yelp, so maybe this isn't that big of an additional deal. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The other precendent for this is Google Flu Trends, which promises to use Google searches to map flu outbreaks. &lt;a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/03/in-defense-of-google-flu-trends/359688/" target="_blank"&gt;There's been debate &lt;/a&gt;about how useful Google Flu Trends really is - sometimes it's works, sometimes it doesn't -- but the reasonable takeaway is that both of these represent one more diagnostic tool for the people whose job it is to stop mass epidemics of vomiting. Which seems all to the good. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.fastcompany.com/3031043/fast-feed/new-york-city-is-using-your-yelp-reviews-to-find-health-code-violations" target="_blank"&gt;(h/t Fast Company)&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</summary><category term="health"></category><category term="technology"></category><category term="yelp"></category></entry><entry><title>All The Worst People Would Like the Internet To Forget Them
</title><link href="http://www.onthemedia.org/story/all-worst-people-would-internet-forget-them/" rel="alternate"></link><updated>2014-05-16T15:17:15-04:00</updated><id>http://www.onthemedia.org/story/all-worst-people-would-internet-forget-them/</id><summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;"The Right to Be Forgotten" is an idea that you should be able to redact information about yourself from internet search results.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It seems like a crazy thing to propose - (Isn't it just a more poetic name for censorship? Who would decide who gets to be forgotten, and why?) but a few governments have instituted some version of legally mandated forgetfulness, most recently the European Union. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now, the BBC is reporting that the first applicants who'd like material removed from the internet have shown up, and they're archetypal examples of people who you'd want to know (factually correct) bad information about. For instance, &lt;a href="http://www.bbc.com/news/technology-27423527" target="_blank"&gt;a guy who got caught possessing child abuse images.&lt;/a&gt; Or an ex-politician making a comeback who wants an article about his bad behavior in office nixed. Or a &lt;a href="http://www.bbc.com/news/technology-27439194" target="_blank"&gt;fellow who tried to kill his family.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The promise of Right to be Forgotten laws is that they'll legislatively fix something about the internet that's essentially unfixable - it's a place where gossip and outrage proliferate, whether or not their targets deserve it. But the solution they offer -- for governments to decide which speech is accurate or worthwhile, is a silly one. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(&lt;a href="http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20140516/06025427252/pedophile-embarrassed-politician-disliked-doctor-kick-off-attempts-to-delete-their-histories-google.shtml" target="_blank"&gt;via the indispensable techdirt&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;
</summary><category term="google"></category><category term="privacy"></category><category term="right_to_be_forgotten"></category><category term="technology"></category></entry><entry><title>Flappy Bird's Creator Says The Game Will Return But Be Less Addictive
</title><link href="http://www.onthemedia.org/story/flappy-birds-creator-says-game-will-return-be-less-addictive/" rel="alternate"></link><updated>2014-05-15T12:10:40-04:00</updated><id>http://www.onthemedia.org/story/flappy-birds-creator-says-game-will-return-be-less-addictive/</id><summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;Flappy Bird is coming back in August. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Quick refresher - &lt;a href="http://www.onthemedia.org/story/flappy-bird-dead-why/" target="_blank"&gt;Flappy Bird was the suddenly ubiquituous mobile game that stormed the world and then disappeared just as quickly.&lt;/a&gt; Developer Dong Nguyen withdrew the game from the internet. At the time, Nguyen &lt;span&gt;said that the game was too addictive. It was bad for the people who played it, and it's success was bad for him. &lt;a href="http://www.cnbc.com/id/101673850" target="_blank"&gt;Nguyen says that the new version of the game will be less addictive. &lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I'm really excited to see what that looks like. Video games are the only entertainment I can think of where the term "addictive" is so often deployed as a mostly positive descriptor.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To be fair, I'm not confident that when gamers talk about something as addictive they mean it in a pure, DSM-definition way. But if you've ever played a video game that's truly addictive, video game addiction feels like kin to real addiction. There's a need for repetition, a feeling of the world slipping by, of whatever bodily needs you have (to eat, to pee) fading. You get home from work on Friday, shut the door, and don't reappear until Monday morning. Maybe it's a Fisher-Price addiction, but it can feel real enough. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are also games that are wonderful and entertaining and &lt;em&gt;not &lt;/em&gt;particularly addictive. &lt;a href="http://www.swordandsworcery.com/" target="_blank"&gt;Sometimes even explicitly so - the iOS game Swords and Sorcery periodically suggests that you take a break &lt;/a&gt;from playing it. I'm excited to watch someone try to make an addictive video game into something more mild. &lt;/p&gt;
